WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.590 --> 00:00:03.326
Professor Charles
Bailyn: I've been talking

00:00:03.326 --> 00:00:05.727
about general relativity,
and in particular,

00:00:05.727 --> 00:00:08.240
the post-Newtonian,
relativistic effects.

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:12.691
These are the first things that
happen as the gravitational

00:00:12.691 --> 00:00:17.372
field becomes strong enough that
Newton's laws don't perfectly

00:00:17.372 --> 00:00:19.957
apply.
And let me just summarize

00:00:19.957 --> 00:00:24.392
those, because we're going to
see them all in action in just a

00:00:24.392 --> 00:00:29.880
minute.
So, here are the post-Newtonian

00:00:29.880 --> 00:00:37.280
effects of general relativity.
And the first of them is the

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:43.690
precession of the perihelion.
I'm just going to list these.

00:00:43.690 --> 00:00:49.227
And this was seen in the
nineteenth century already,

00:00:49.227 --> 00:00:53.570
and correctly interpreted by
Einstein.

00:00:53.570 --> 00:00:56.100
It had to do with Mercury's
orbit.

00:00:56.100 --> 00:00:58.596
I should say,
this word, perihelion,

00:00:58.596 --> 00:01:01.520
that means closest approach to
the Sun.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:04.545
And so, that only applies for
planets if you have the

00:01:04.545 --> 00:01:08.210
same--you can have the same kind
of effect in binary stars or in

00:01:08.210 --> 00:01:10.723
other things,
in which case,

00:01:10.723 --> 00:01:14.860
you might--they call it a
periastron.

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:18.870
That's the closest approach to
a star that isn't the Sun.

00:01:18.870 --> 00:01:25.112
Or, here's a favorite word of
mine: perigalacticon,

00:01:25.112 --> 00:01:29.662
I like that one.
That's the closest approach to

00:01:29.662 --> 00:01:33.179
a galaxy.
You can have--the other side of

00:01:33.179 --> 00:01:38.323
the orbit that is 180 degrees
away from the perigalacticon,

00:01:38.323 --> 00:01:41.959
that's called the
anti-perigalacticon.

00:01:41.959 --> 00:01:46.073
And you are challenged to use
that in a sentence at any time

00:01:46.073 --> 00:01:48.708
over break.
Anyone who successfully does

00:01:48.708 --> 00:01:51.855
that, send me an email
recounting the circumstances,

00:01:51.855 --> 00:01:54.879
and I'll give you an extra
point or something.

00:01:54.879 --> 00:01:58.799
All right, so,
precession of the perihelion,

00:01:58.799 --> 00:02:01.989
that's one post-Newtonian
effect.

00:02:01.989 --> 00:02:07.092
Another post-Newtonian effect
is the deflection of light by

00:02:07.092 --> 00:02:11.403
mass, just because mass curves
space-time, and so,

00:02:11.403 --> 00:02:15.009
light will follow a curved path
also.

00:02:15.009 --> 00:02:18.876
This was first demonstrated in
1919 by the famous eclipse

00:02:18.876 --> 00:02:20.810
observations of Eddington.

00:02:24.020 --> 00:02:30.458
And it also has been manifested
recently in the discovery of

00:02:30.458 --> 00:02:35.792
so-called gravitational lenses,
of various kinds,

00:02:35.792 --> 00:02:41.908
in which the appearance of an
object is distorted by the fact

00:02:41.908 --> 00:02:48.126
that the light from that object
has to pass by some other mass

00:02:48.126 --> 00:02:52.180
on its way to your eye.
And so, I have a couple

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:54.477
examples, here,
which I'd like to show you of

00:02:54.477 --> 00:02:55.730
gravitational lenses.

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:07.030
This is the famous Einstein
cross, so-called.

00:03:07.030 --> 00:03:10.027
And what this is,
this is just a picture,

00:03:10.027 --> 00:03:13.250
I think, from the Hubble Space
Telescope.

00:03:13.250 --> 00:03:17.940
And these four objects,
here, are the same object.

00:03:17.940 --> 00:03:21.236
That's a quasar.
It's just, for this purpose,

00:03:21.236 --> 00:03:25.099
a point of light in the sky.
But it's located--its true

00:03:25.099 --> 00:03:29.173
location is behind this thing.
This is much closer to you than

00:03:29.173 --> 00:03:32.975
any of these guys.
This is a galaxy about partway

00:03:32.975 --> 00:03:36.742
between us and the quasar.
And what has happened is,

00:03:36.742 --> 00:03:39.865
if there were no deflection of
light, you'd see this quasar,

00:03:39.865 --> 00:03:41.770
kind of, right behind the
galaxy.

00:03:41.770 --> 00:03:44.152
And in fact,
it would be hard to distinguish

00:03:44.152 --> 00:03:46.631
between the two.
But what has happened is,

00:03:46.631 --> 00:03:50.008
because there's this galaxy in
the way, the light from the

00:03:50.008 --> 00:03:53.622
quasar starts coming this way
and then bends around the galaxy

00:03:53.622 --> 00:03:56.964
and comes back toward us.
And the same is true up here

00:03:56.964 --> 00:03:58.639
and down here,
and down here.

00:03:58.639 --> 00:04:02.980
And so, you get four different
images of this quasar--of the

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:05.216
same quasar.
And they know it's the same

00:04:05.216 --> 00:04:07.450
quasar, because they've taken
spectra of the thing,

00:04:07.450 --> 00:04:09.773
and it's the exact same
spectrum on all four of these

00:04:09.773 --> 00:04:12.427
things.
And so, these are just four

00:04:12.427 --> 00:04:15.330
different images of the same
object.

00:04:15.330 --> 00:04:18.194
And the reason they're not
symmetrically distributed,

00:04:18.194 --> 00:04:21.498
here, is because the mass in
this galaxy is not symmetrically

00:04:21.498 --> 00:04:24.267
distributed.
And so, depending on what path

00:04:24.267 --> 00:04:27.540
you take, you get different
amounts of deflections.

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:31.140
So, that's a classic example of
gravitational lens.

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:32.615
Yes?
Student: Why can't we

00:04:32.615 --> 00:04:33.649
also see this quasar in the
middle?

00:04:33.649 --> 00:04:35.766
Professor Charles
Bailyn: In principle,

00:04:35.766 --> 00:04:37.459
you could see it,
right through here,

00:04:37.459 --> 00:04:40.610
but there are two things about
the path that comes right at us.

00:04:40.610 --> 00:04:42.629
There are two problems with
that.

00:04:42.629 --> 00:04:46.628
One is that for various--these
guys are all magnified,

00:04:46.628 --> 00:04:51.079
and the one that comes through
the middle is demagnified.

00:04:51.079 --> 00:04:53.395
Second of all,
it's right in back of the

00:04:53.395 --> 00:04:54.817
galaxy.
But, in principle,

00:04:54.817 --> 00:04:57.430
there's a fifth one down in the
middle, that's true.

00:04:57.430 --> 00:05:00.629
Yes?
Student: [Inaudible]

00:05:00.629 --> 00:05:02.540
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Sorry?

00:05:02.540 --> 00:05:04.851
Student: [Inaudible]
Professor Charles

00:05:04.851 --> 00:05:06.474
Bailyn: Okay,
so what--let me,

00:05:06.474 --> 00:05:08.343
let me pause,
here, and tell you what a

00:05:08.343 --> 00:05:11.953
quasar is.
A quasar is a quasi-stellar

00:05:11.953 --> 00:05:13.724
object.
What it is, is,

00:05:13.724 --> 00:05:17.399
it's a very bright source right
in the middle of a galaxy.

00:05:17.399 --> 00:05:21.760
And so, it's actually a point
source of light.

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:24.075
It looks like a star.
These things turns out to

00:05:24.075 --> 00:05:25.923
be--what they really are,
it turns out,

00:05:25.923 --> 00:05:28.500
are massive black holes in the
center of galaxies,

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:32.949
accreting material from the
galaxy itself.

00:05:32.949 --> 00:05:37.769
But they appear to be very
bright nuclei of galaxies and if

00:05:37.769 --> 00:05:41.774
you could look really hard,
you could see the galaxy--the

00:05:41.774 --> 00:05:43.810
background galaxy around this
thing.

00:05:43.810 --> 00:05:46.750
But in this particular case,
it's way too faint to see.

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:50.567
The galaxy has a much larger
extent, because it's all the

00:05:50.567 --> 00:05:53.430
stars and all the stuff in the
galaxies.

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:55.970
It's not coming right from the
middle.

00:05:55.970 --> 00:05:58.545
And this one's much closer than
those, and so,

00:05:58.545 --> 00:06:01.750
you can actually see that it's
extended, in this case.

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:03.912
Yes?
Student: [Inaudible]

00:06:03.912 --> 00:06:05.705
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Oh,

00:06:05.705 --> 00:06:08.420
it's not the black hole that's
emitting the light.

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:11.728
It's the material falling into
the black hole that gets heated

00:06:11.728 --> 00:06:13.602
up.
I'll actually talk about this

00:06:13.602 --> 00:06:17.428
on Thursday a little bit.
Other questions about the

00:06:17.428 --> 00:06:19.530
Einstein cross,
here?

00:06:19.530 --> 00:06:20.430
Let me show you another one.

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:27.721
So, this is a Hubble Space
Telescope picture of a cluster

00:06:27.721 --> 00:06:30.197
of galaxies.
See all these different things,

00:06:30.197 --> 00:06:32.676
all these extended sources,
those are all individual

00:06:32.676 --> 00:06:34.729
galaxies.
Galaxies, it turns out,

00:06:34.729 --> 00:06:37.740
come in clusters.
And so, here is a big bunch of

00:06:37.740 --> 00:06:40.076
galaxies.
And some of the galaxies you

00:06:40.076 --> 00:06:43.143
see here--most of the galaxies,
all these big ones,

00:06:43.143 --> 00:06:46.443
are part of this cluster.
This is a cluster that's

00:06:46.443 --> 00:06:49.930
relatively nearby to Earth.
But some of the galaxies are

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:53.210
actually not in the cluster.
They're much, much further away.

00:06:53.210 --> 00:06:56.310
They're in back of the cluster.
And these things--these,

00:06:56.310 --> 00:07:00.436
sort of, streaky things you see
all over the place here--what

00:07:00.436 --> 00:07:03.508
these are,
are galaxies that are in back

00:07:03.508 --> 00:07:07.564
of the cluster of galaxies,
whose light has been lensed

00:07:07.564 --> 00:07:11.320
when it passes through the
cluster of galaxies.

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:13.910
And it's been stretched.
It's because,

00:07:13.910 --> 00:07:15.917
what happened is,
this thing here,

00:07:15.917 --> 00:07:18.166
for example,
ought to be a tiny little

00:07:18.166 --> 00:07:20.660
galaxy that you can barely see
here,

00:07:20.660 --> 00:07:25.020
except the light from the top
end of that galaxy got bent up

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:27.455
to here.
And the light from the bottom

00:07:27.455 --> 00:07:29.910
end of that galaxy got bent down
to here.

00:07:29.910 --> 00:07:33.450
And that's why they're all sort
of in this kind of--all these

00:07:33.450 --> 00:07:37.110
things are kind of circular
around the center of this thing,

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:39.209
because this is a very,
very massive galaxy.

00:07:39.209 --> 00:07:41.529
And that's the thing that's
doing the lensing.

00:07:41.529 --> 00:07:45.607
And so, it effectively distorts
the shape of the background

00:07:45.607 --> 00:07:47.988
galaxy.
And you can see a couple more

00:07:47.988 --> 00:07:50.519
of them around this massive
galaxy, here.

00:07:50.519 --> 00:07:54.795
These are pretty,
but they also can be used in

00:07:54.795 --> 00:07:59.925
order to understand the
distribution of mass inside the

00:07:59.925 --> 00:08:03.636
galaxy cluster.
Because the particular way in

00:08:03.636 --> 00:08:07.120
which these galaxies are
distorted depends on how much

00:08:07.120 --> 00:08:09.750
mass there is in this galaxy
cluster,

00:08:09.750 --> 00:08:11.949
and how that mass is
distributed.

00:08:11.949 --> 00:08:18.573
And so, these are used to study
the mass distributions of galaxy

00:08:18.573 --> 00:08:21.908
clusters.
And so, this is a different

00:08:21.908 --> 00:08:25.713
kind of gravitational lensing.
And finally,

00:08:25.713 --> 00:08:30.428
let me show you a joke.
This is a picture of The

00:08:30.428 --> 00:08:34.030
Smithsonian Institute in
Washington, D.C.,

00:08:34.030 --> 00:08:37.973
where there are a group--well,
actually, The Smithsonian

00:08:37.973 --> 00:08:40.060
Astrophysical Observatory is
actually in Cambridge,

00:08:40.060 --> 00:08:42.551
Massachusetts.
And there, there are a group of

00:08:42.551 --> 00:08:44.850
people who study gravitational
lensing.

00:08:44.850 --> 00:08:46.759
And they have taken this
picture.

00:08:46.759 --> 00:08:50.057
And imagine what it would look
like if, about halfway between

00:08:50.057 --> 00:08:53.190
where you're looking and this
building, there were a black

00:08:53.190 --> 00:08:57.759
hole the mass of Saturn.
And here's what it looks like.

00:08:57.759 --> 00:09:02.184
And all these distortions are
simply due to the change in

00:09:02.184 --> 00:09:06.134
direction caused by the
gravitational force of this

00:09:06.134 --> 00:09:10.004
imaginary black hole.
And so, you could see what

00:09:10.004 --> 00:09:11.479
happens.
The black hole is,

00:09:11.479 --> 00:09:13.210
sort of, right down the middle,
here.

00:09:13.210 --> 00:09:16.141
And so, off at the edges,
there's only a little bit of

00:09:16.141 --> 00:09:17.824
distortion.
And then, in the middle,

00:09:17.824 --> 00:09:21.590
everything goes haywire.
Let me take this back a notch.

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:24.342
Take a look at these two
central towers,

00:09:24.342 --> 00:09:26.529
this one, here,
and that one.

00:09:26.529 --> 00:09:29.509
And so, they're kind of--what's
happened, here,

00:09:29.509 --> 00:09:33.265
is that you're seeing light
that has gone out and then been

00:09:33.265 --> 00:09:36.182
bent back towards you,
so, it looks like the tower's

00:09:36.182 --> 00:09:38.868
over here.
But look, that same tower is

00:09:38.868 --> 00:09:41.895
down here.
And so, that's light from the

00:09:41.895 --> 00:09:45.835
tower that went down and
underneath the black hole and

00:09:45.835 --> 00:09:49.179
then got pulled back up to reach
your eye.

00:09:49.179 --> 00:09:51.848
So, there are two paths from
that tower to your eye,

00:09:51.848 --> 00:09:54.930
and you can see both of them.
Look at this thing here.

00:09:54.930 --> 00:09:57.823
What's that?
Let me go back to the original

00:09:57.823 --> 00:10:00.250
picture.
That's this statue.

00:10:00.250 --> 00:10:03.214
And what's happened is,
light from the top of the

00:10:03.214 --> 00:10:06.672
statue has gone up and over the
black hole, and come down

00:10:06.672 --> 00:10:10.529
towards you.
Whoops--and so, here it is.

00:10:10.529 --> 00:10:13.630
And similarly,
the clouds that were up here

00:10:13.630 --> 00:10:17.986
have been bent down--have gone
underneath the black hole and

00:10:17.986 --> 00:10:21.529
been bent back up,
so you can see them here.

00:10:21.529 --> 00:10:24.193
And so, they worked out all the
distortions of this,

00:10:24.193 --> 00:10:27.169
and so, they like to show this
kind of amusing picture.

00:10:27.169 --> 00:10:30.692
They actually had a movie,
which I couldn't find on the

00:10:30.692 --> 00:10:33.039
Net, last night,
which is too bad,

00:10:33.039 --> 00:10:35.963
where they take the black hole,
and they kind of move it across

00:10:35.963 --> 00:10:38.545
the front of this thing.
You can see all the distortions

00:10:38.545 --> 00:10:41.179
coming out.
And so, you can have enormous

00:10:41.179 --> 00:10:44.283
fun with this kind of thing.
Needless to say,

00:10:44.283 --> 00:10:47.824
this is not--this particular
picture has not ever actually

00:10:47.824 --> 00:10:50.978
been observed.
That's calculated,

00:10:50.978 --> 00:10:55.800
not actually observed.
But, you can see the kinds of

00:10:55.800 --> 00:10:59.121
bizarre effects that
gravitational lensing can

00:10:59.121 --> 00:10:59.860
create.

00:11:04.100 --> 00:11:05.858
And, as I mentioned,
in some cases,

00:11:05.858 --> 00:11:08.650
these are scientifically useful
things, because you can

00:11:08.650 --> 00:11:11.546
determine the distribution of
the mass that's causing the

00:11:11.546 --> 00:11:13.570
lensing.
Questions? Yes?

00:11:13.570 --> 00:11:17.257
Student: So in that
particular case it's always

00:11:17.257 --> 00:11:19.901
[Inaudible]
that all the light from the

00:11:19.901 --> 00:11:22.629
other side get lensed?
Professor Charles

00:11:22.629 --> 00:11:24.836
Bailyn: Well,
what you have to do--it depends

00:11:24.836 --> 00:11:27.549
a little bit on the exact mass
distribution of the lens.

00:11:27.549 --> 00:11:29.247
In this case,
I think they're assuming a

00:11:29.247 --> 00:11:30.754
point source.
And so, it is,

00:11:30.754 --> 00:11:33.990
in general, true that if
there's a gravitational lens,

00:11:33.990 --> 00:11:37.470
you end up seeing more light
than you otherwise would,

00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:39.580
because it's focused in towards
you.

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:41.941
So, the total amount of light
that you see,

00:11:41.941 --> 00:11:43.909
if you're seeing a lensed
object,

00:11:43.909 --> 00:11:47.202
is typically larger than the
amount you would see in the

00:11:47.202 --> 00:11:49.899
absence of the lens.
So, there are more paths of

00:11:49.899 --> 00:11:52.862
light that are curved towards
you than are curved away from

00:11:52.862 --> 00:11:54.950
you.
If you're standing over on the

00:11:54.950 --> 00:11:57.431
side, you'll lose a little bit
of the light,

00:11:57.431 --> 00:12:00.490
because it will be curved in
some other direction.

00:12:00.490 --> 00:12:03.549
And so, there are more
different way--you can see the

00:12:03.549 --> 00:12:06.315
thing--you know,
it's kind of an early twentieth

00:12:06.315 --> 00:12:09.286
century art thing.
You can see the same object

00:12:09.286 --> 00:12:12.888
from two different sides at
once, and you get these curious

00:12:12.888 --> 00:12:15.009
distortions.
Yes?

00:12:15.009 --> 00:12:17.532
Student: If you're
looking into a galaxy cluster

00:12:17.532 --> 00:12:20.288
and there are a lot of streaks
and a lot of galaxies and you

00:12:20.288 --> 00:12:22.904
don't know the mass of the
galaxy to try to find the mass

00:12:22.904 --> 00:12:24.352
[Inaudible]
Professor Charles

00:12:24.352 --> 00:12:26.808
Bailyn: Yeah.
Student: How do you know

00:12:26.808 --> 00:12:28.429
what streaks belong to which
galaxies?

00:12:28.429 --> 00:12:29.866
Professor Charles
Bailyn: What streaks belong

00:12:29.866 --> 00:12:30.850
to which galaxies?
Okay.

00:12:30.850 --> 00:12:34.513
You know that the streaks must
come from galaxies that are

00:12:34.513 --> 00:12:38.177
located behind the galaxy
cluster, that are not themselves

00:12:38.177 --> 00:12:41.854
part of the galaxy cluster.
And, in order to understand

00:12:41.854 --> 00:12:43.912
what that streak is,
in principle,

00:12:43.912 --> 00:12:47.779
you'd need to know the exact
shape and size of that galaxy.

00:12:47.779 --> 00:12:50.289
You can go and take a spectrum
of the thing and figure out how

00:12:50.289 --> 00:12:52.470
far away it is and what the
relative distances are.

00:12:52.470 --> 00:12:54.640
But, in principle,
you would need to know the

00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:57.106
exact shape of that galaxy
before it was distorted,

00:12:57.106 --> 00:13:00.262
which you don't know.
And so, what you have to do,

00:13:00.262 --> 00:13:03.900
to interpret these things,
is to take many streaks and

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:07.470
assume that the galaxies that
caused them are kind of

00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:11.039
normal--a normal distribution of
galaxy shapes.

00:13:11.039 --> 00:13:14.100
And so, it's more of a
statistical process than using

00:13:14.100 --> 00:13:16.159
them one at a time,
in that case.

00:13:16.159 --> 00:13:18.556
The quasars are a little easier
to deal with,

00:13:18.556 --> 00:13:20.679
because you know that they're
points.

00:13:20.679 --> 00:13:23.857
And this--and there are various
kinds of limits to how much

00:13:23.857 --> 00:13:25.940
