00:14:37.370 --> 00:14:41.395
Now, the deflection of light.
Moving on, number three,

00:14:41.395 --> 00:14:45.698
here, is what we talked about
last time, which is the

00:14:45.698 --> 00:14:47.850
gravitational redshift.

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:58.529
And here, we have delta lambda
over lambda [Δ λ/ λ],

00:14:58.529 --> 00:15:02.262
or alternatively,
in the case of the problem set

00:15:02.262 --> 00:15:05.636
you're working on,
the pulse period,

00:15:05.636 --> 00:15:10.325
in either case--these are
usually given the letter

00:15:10.325 --> 00:15:14.811
Z, that's redshift.
That's a definition of this

00:15:14.811 --> 00:15:17.409
quantity, Z,
which is often used.

00:15:17.409 --> 00:15:21.830
And this is equal to this
quantity.

00:15:28.149 --> 00:15:38.010
And this is the Schwarzschild
radius of some mass.

00:15:41.210 --> 00:15:49.665
And this R is the
distance of the light source

00:15:49.665 --> 00:15:52.430
from that mass.

00:15:55.679 --> 00:16:03.922
And what this equation
signifies is how much redshift

00:16:03.922 --> 00:16:13.117
is there, if you observe this
thing when you are sitting at

00:16:13.117 --> 00:16:21.360
infinity--do you observe from
infinite distance.

00:16:21.360 --> 00:16:22.950
And what do I mean by infinite
distance?

00:16:22.950 --> 00:16:26.134
What I mean is that
R_S / R

00:16:26.134 --> 00:16:29.676
goes to zero.
That's what infinite R

00:16:29.676 --> 00:16:33.008
means, in this case.
So, you're sitting out there a

00:16:33.008 --> 00:16:35.779
long, long, long way away from
any gravitational effect.

00:16:35.779 --> 00:16:38.662
You're looking at a light that
is emitted inside a

00:16:38.662 --> 00:16:41.779
gravitational field,
relatively close to some mass.

00:16:41.779 --> 00:16:46.210
That light is redshifted by
this amount.

00:16:46.210 --> 00:16:49.656
And pulse periods are also
lengthened by the same amount,

00:16:49.656 --> 00:16:52.179
and I'll come back to that in a
minute.

00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:56.049
One thing I want to say right
now is, what happens if you are

00:16:56.049 --> 00:16:59.210
an observer and you're not
infinitely far away?

00:16:59.210 --> 00:17:02.074
What happens if you're just a
little bit further away than the

00:17:02.074 --> 00:17:04.722
light source is,
or perhaps even if you're

00:17:04.722 --> 00:17:08.109
closer to the object than the
light source is?

00:17:08.109 --> 00:17:16.356
And, in that case,
if the observer is not at

00:17:16.356 --> 00:17:26.137
infinity, then the observed
redshift is equal to the

00:17:26.137 --> 00:17:34.000
redshift from the source to
infinity,

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:38.639
which you could calculate by
this formula,

00:17:38.639 --> 00:17:44.410
minus the redshift from the
observer to infinity,

00:17:44.410 --> 00:17:48.799
which you can also calculate
with that same formula.

00:17:48.799 --> 00:17:51.599
So, you have to subtract two
things.

00:17:51.599 --> 00:17:54.332
Basically, what happens is,
imagine the light going

00:17:54.332 --> 00:17:56.299
from--it starts out at the
source,

00:17:56.299 --> 00:17:59.014
it goes to the observer,
and then it keeps going all the

00:17:59.014 --> 00:18:01.254
way out to infinity.
And you want to ask,

00:18:01.254 --> 00:18:04.823
what does the observer see?
The observer sees that portion

00:18:04.823 --> 00:18:08.338
of the redshift that happens
between the source and the

00:18:08.338 --> 00:18:10.895
observer.
So, to figure out what that is,

00:18:10.895 --> 00:18:14.160
you figure out the redshift
from the source to infinity.

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:17.510
You figure out the redshift
from the observer to infinity.

00:18:17.510 --> 00:18:21.327
And you subtract those things.
And that gives you the redshift

00:18:21.327 --> 00:18:25.869
from the source to the observer.
Okay, yes?

00:18:25.869 --> 00:18:29.338
Student: [Inaudible]
Professor Charles

00:18:29.338 --> 00:18:32.880
