00:18:36.551 --> 00:18:39.440
there is no redshift.
That means there is no redshift.

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:42.720
It doesn't mean that the
observed wavelength is zero.

00:18:42.720 --> 00:18:46.880
It means the change in the
wavelength is zero.

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:51.197
Yeah, that's important.
And, just to comment on the

00:18:51.197 --> 00:18:55.143
problem set here,
the idea on the second problem

00:18:55.143 --> 00:18:59.174
of the problem set is,
you do have an observer at

00:18:59.174 --> 00:19:01.760
infinity.
So, here's the observer.

00:19:01.760 --> 00:19:05.950
Here's some neutron star.
And you have a light source

00:19:05.950 --> 00:19:10.052
that can either be on the
surface of the neutron star,

00:19:10.052 --> 00:19:14.619
or it can be raised off the
surface of the neutron star.

00:19:14.619 --> 00:19:18.116
And basically,
what you're observing is the

00:19:18.116 --> 00:19:22.795
change in the light source.
So, this has some redshift,

00:19:22.795 --> 00:19:27.326
some pretty large redshift,
because it's sitting on the

00:19:27.326 --> 00:19:32.527
surface of a neutron star.
This, because it's further away

00:19:32.527 --> 00:19:37.079
from the neutron star,
has slightly less redshift.

00:19:37.079 --> 00:19:43.609
And what you are interested in
is the change in the redshift.

00:19:43.609 --> 00:19:47.329
And the idea behind the problem
is, you want to set this up so

00:19:47.329 --> 00:19:51.232
that that change in the redshift
is the same as the change in the

00:19:51.232 --> 00:19:53.549
redshift due to the Doppler
shift,

00:19:53.549 --> 00:19:56.819
if this whole thing was in
orbit around something.

00:19:56.819 --> 00:20:00.660
That's the plan of that
particular problem.

00:20:07.279 --> 00:20:13.981
Okay, so that's the third of
the post-Newtonian relativistic

00:20:13.981 --> 00:20:18.069
effects, and there's a fourth
one.

00:20:18.069 --> 00:20:23.259
The fourth is gravitational
waves, which I may have time to

00:20:23.259 --> 00:20:26.569
come back and talk about in
detail.

00:20:26.569 --> 00:20:29.349
At the moment,
though, I just want to say what

00:20:29.349 --> 00:20:32.807
the effect of these things is,
rather than talk in detail

00:20:32.807 --> 00:20:36.914
about what they are.
The effect is that the orbital

00:20:36.914 --> 00:20:38.490
period decreases.

00:20:43.549 --> 00:20:48.566
Now, it turns out,
this is a relatively small

00:20:48.566 --> 00:20:54.609
effect, and it is not observed
in the Solar System,

00:20:54.609 --> 00:20:57.308
even in Mercury,
which has the strongest

00:20:57.308 --> 00:20:58.830
relativistic effect.

00:21:05.640 --> 00:21:07.584
Okay.
So, those are four

00:21:07.584 --> 00:21:11.759
post-Newtonian effects of
general relativity.

00:21:11.759 --> 00:21:16.783
And what I want to talk about
now is what has become probably

00:21:16.783 --> 00:21:21.890
the best laboratory for general
relativity that we know of.

00:21:21.890 --> 00:21:24.142
The problem with general
relativity is you can't actually

00:21:24.142 --> 00:21:25.589
study it all that much in the
lab,

00:21:25.589 --> 00:21:29.390
because, in order to study it,
you need strong gravitational

00:21:29.390 --> 00:21:31.400
forces.
And it's very difficult to

00:21:31.400 --> 00:21:34.260
create strong gravitational
forces in a laboratory.

00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:37.291
What would you need to do?
You'd need to take some massive

00:21:37.291 --> 00:21:39.779
object, crush it down to the
size of a black hole or

00:21:39.779 --> 00:21:42.119
something, and have it sit there
in your lab.

00:21:42.119 --> 00:21:44.559
And this is not something that
one can do.

00:21:44.559 --> 00:21:48.307
And so, you have to go and look
at astronomical objects in order

00:21:48.307 --> 00:21:51.222
to find suitable situation in
which to study these

00:21:51.222 --> 00:21:56.222
relativistic effects.
So, the best lab for general

00:21:56.222 --> 00:22:02.869
relativity--lab for G.R.,
here, is a set of objects.

00:22:02.869 --> 00:22:06.292
And one object in particular,
which is referred to as the

00:22:06.292 --> 00:22:08.841
Binary Pulsar.
This is discussed in the

00:22:08.841 --> 00:22:11.329
readings for this week's problem
set.

00:22:11.329 --> 00:22:15.557
The discovery of this
particular object led to a Nobel

00:22:15.557 --> 00:22:20.024
Prize for its discoverers,
and that's what's discussed in

00:22:20.024 --> 00:22:23.557
that article.
So, the first thing to talk

00:22:23.557 --> 00:22:26.299
about, here, is what is a
pulsar?

00:22:26.299 --> 00:22:39.599
So, pulsars were discovered in
the late 1960s by a woman named

00:22:39.599 --> 00:22:44.976
Jocelyn Bell.
And she wired up a whole field

00:22:44.976 --> 00:22:48.065
in Cambridge,
England, to make it behave like

00:22:48.065 --> 00:22:52.045
a radio telescope,
and discovered that there were

00:22:52.045 --> 00:22:55.136
objects in the sky,
celestial objects,

00:22:55.136 --> 00:22:59.480
that seemed to be emitting
pulses of radio waves.

00:22:59.480 --> 00:23:05.404
So, the observed signature of
these things--what was observed

00:23:05.404 --> 00:23:09.554
is pulses of radio waves.
So, you get kind of a blip

00:23:09.554 --> 00:23:11.431
every few seconds.
It goes blip,

00:23:11.431 --> 00:23:13.380
blip, blip, blip,
and so forth.

00:23:13.380 --> 00:23:21.509
And these pulses come by--so,
the pulsations happen

00:23:21.509 --> 00:23:29.964
once--it's sort of with a period
of somewhere between

00:23:29.964 --> 00:23:36.589
milliseconds and ten seconds.
So, they come at you pretty

00:23:36.589 --> 00:23:37.010
rapidly.

00:23:41.819 --> 00:23:44.819
Most of them are a few seconds
or maybe a fraction of a second.

00:23:44.819 --> 00:23:48.069
So, these things are blipping
away.

00:23:48.069 --> 00:23:50.230
And they had no idea what these
were.

00:23:50.230 --> 00:23:54.400
And the first four of them they
gave the nickname LGM1,

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:56.041
LGM2,
LGM3,

00:23:56.041 --> 00:23:58.981
LGM4,
for "little green men," because

00:23:58.981 --> 00:24:03.220
the thought was that these might
actually--they thought,

00:24:03.220 --> 00:24:05.236
briefly, that these might be
signals from some

00:24:05.236 --> 00:24:07.577
extraterrestrial intelligence,
because, you know,

00:24:07.577 --> 00:24:10.670
it's a very regular signal.
It's hard to imagine how those

00:24:10.670 --> 00:24:12.890
could have been created.
But, fortunately,

00:24:12.890 --> 00:24:15.496
before they published their
paper, somebody suggested a

00:24:15.496 --> 00:24:17.910
better solution,
which turns out to be correct.

00:24:17.910 --> 00:24:26.478
That what these things are,
are rotating magnetized neutron

00:24:26.478 --> 00:24:29.329
stars.
And this was the first direct

00:24:29.329 --> 00:24:31.460
evidence that neutron stars
existed.

00:24:31.460 --> 00:24:35.219
And the reason they thought
they were neutron stars is

00:24:35.219 --> 00:24:39.404
because the speed with which
these things pulsed is supposed

00:24:39.404 --> 00:24:43.589
to be reflected in the rotation
of these neutron stars.

00:24:43.589 --> 00:24:46.958
And something that rotates ten
times a second had better be

00:24:46.958 --> 00:24:49.839
pretty small.
And so, there was strong size

00:24:49.839 --> 00:24:53.544
limits on the neutron stars.
It's not going to matter,

00:24:53.544 --> 00:24:57.341
too much, exactly what these
things are, but I'm going to

00:24:57.341 --> 00:25:00.210
explain it to you anyway.
But don't worry too much about

00:25:00.210 --> 00:25:02.187
it.
For the purposes of relativity,

00:25:02.187 --> 00:25:04.868
the key point,
here, is that it's an extremely

00:25:04.868 --> 00:25:08.264
accurate clock--that you get
these blips coming out of the

00:25:08.264 --> 00:25:10.813
thing,
and that creates a very

00:25:10.813 --> 00:25:14.047
accurate clock.
And then, you can see very

00:25:14.047 --> 00:25:17.660
small changes in the pulse rate
of these things.

00:25:17.660 --> 00:25:20.329
So, now let me just briefly
tell you what these are.

00:25:20.329 --> 00:25:24.121
Oh, I should mention--so,
the discovery of neutron stars,

00:25:24.121 --> 00:25:27.355
this was a very big deal.
This was the first strongly

00:25:27.355 --> 00:25:30.323
relativistic object that had
ever been discovered and they

00:25:30.323 --> 00:25:33.500
awarded a Nobel Prize to Jocelyn
Bell's thesis supervisor.

00:25:33.500 --> 00:25:37.924
And there is some feeling among
some folks that this was an

00:25:37.924 --> 00:25:41.212
injustice.
And so, there is--people

00:25:41.212 --> 00:25:46.452
discuss the story of Jocelyn
Bell and the discovery of

00:25:46.452 --> 00:25:48.953
pulsars.
To her credit,

00:25:48.953 --> 00:25:52.915
Bell has never complained.
Bell and the discovery of

00:25:52.915 --> 00:25:55.930
pulsar-- Student: Did the
thesis advisor do anything?

00:25:55.930 --> 00:25:56.877
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Oh yes,

00:25:56.877 --> 00:25:58.019
well that's actually an
interesting question.

00:25:58.019 --> 00:26:00.065
The question is,
"Did the thesis advisor do

00:26:00.065 --> 00:26:02.759
anything?"
As a thesis advisor myself,

00:26:02.759 --> 00:26:07.016
I take that question seriously.
Well, this is the whole debate

00:26:07.016 --> 00:26:09.710
about who should have gotten the
Nobel Prize.

00:26:09.710 --> 00:26:14.084
The thesis supervisor thought
up the experiment,

00:26:14.084 --> 00:26:18.096
and Bell did it.
So, who ought to get the credit

00:26:18.096 --> 00:26:20.640
for that?
It's actually a subtle

00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:23.733
question, and it bears on
problem four,

00:26:23.733 --> 00:26:27.152
or whatever it is,
of this week's homework,

00:26:27.152 --> 00:26:32.126
so it's worth thinking about.
Jocelyn Bell and the discovery

00:26:32.126 --> 00:26:34.700
of pulsars--he also got the
money.

00:26:34.700 --> 00:26:38.688
That's not trivial sometimes.
And the moral of the story--it

00:26:38.688 --> 00:26:41.962
depends on who you ask,
for exactly the reason that you

00:26:41.962 --> 00:26:45.801
bring up.
One moral of the story is that

00:26:45.801 --> 00:26:49.743
grad students,
particularly female grad

00:26:49.743 --> 00:26:55.344
students, never get any credit
and that this is a great

00:26:55.344 --> 00:26:58.184
injustice.
As you get older,

00:26:58.184 --> 00:27:01.509
your attitude towards this
problem changes.

00:27:01.509 --> 00:27:09.308
And the alternative moral is
that thinking and doing are not

00:27:09.308 --> 00:27:16.049
the same, and that thinking is
better than doing.

00:27:16.049 --> 00:27:19.758
Now, one could raise various
objections, and people have,

00:27:19.758 --> 00:27:22.734
to this line of thought.
And interestingly enough,

00:27:22.734 --> 00:27:25.746
the next time they had to give
a Nobel Prize for something to

00:27:25.746 --> 00:27:28.633
do with pulsars,
which was the discovery of the

00:27:28.633 --> 00:27:31.533
Binary Pulsar,
they did give the prize also to

00:27:31.533 --> 00:27:35.045
the graduate student.
And it's the graduate student's

