really quickly.
Here's the neutron star,

00:29:29.003 --> 00:29:34.190
still, and now the pole's over
here, because it's rotated

00:29:34.190 --> 00:29:38.730
around by a factor of two,
by half a rotation.

00:29:38.730 --> 00:29:41.450
So, now the radio emission's
coming this way.

00:29:41.450 --> 00:29:44.112
And if you're still sitting
observing the thing down here,

00:29:44.112 --> 00:29:49.690
you don't see anything.
So this is on, and this is off.

00:29:49.690 --> 00:29:52.239
So, you watch this pole.
It's sort of like a lighthouse,

00:29:52.239 --> 00:29:54.032
you know.
A lighthouse has a beam of

00:29:54.032 --> 00:29:55.778
light.
And when it's pointing towards

00:29:55.778 --> 00:29:58.011
you, you see light.
And then, as it's going around

00:29:58.011 --> 00:29:59.509
in a circle, you don't see
light.

00:29:59.509 --> 00:30:01.480
Then it points towards you--you
see light again.

00:30:01.480 --> 00:30:05.839
And so, the consequence of this
is that you get something that

00:30:05.839 --> 00:30:09.269
looks--if you plot radio
emission versus time,

00:30:09.269 --> 00:30:14.690
you get these very regularly
spaced blips.

00:30:14.690 --> 00:30:19.496
And it is the time between one
blip and the next that's the

00:30:19.496 --> 00:30:20.740
pulse period.

00:30:25.630 --> 00:30:27.459
And so, for our purposes
here--I mean,

00:30:27.459 --> 00:30:30.376
pulsars are very interesting
objects, but we're not going to

00:30:30.376 --> 00:30:33.691
go into them in any depth.
As objects, the key thing is

00:30:33.691 --> 00:30:36.829
that it's got this really
accurate clock on it.

00:30:36.829 --> 00:30:40.342
And if you imagine a pulsar in
orbit around something,

00:30:40.342 --> 00:30:44.120
when it comes towards you,
each one of these blips happens

00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:47.868
a little closer to you.
So, the light travel time from

00:30:47.868 --> 00:30:51.093
the blip to you is less.
And so, it seems like the blips

00:30:51.093 --> 00:30:53.715
happen closer together,
because each one of them has

00:30:53.715 --> 00:30:55.720
emitted a little closer towards
you.

00:30:55.720 --> 00:30:59.066
Similarly, when it's going
away, each blip is emitted a

00:30:59.066 --> 00:31:02.284
little further away.
It takes extra time to get to

00:31:02.284 --> 00:31:05.864
you, and the pulse period,
the length of time between the

00:31:05.864 --> 00:31:09.099
pulses, appears to be longer.
By how much?

00:31:09.099 --> 00:31:13.574
By exactly the amount that the
Doppler shift formula would

00:31:13.574 --> 00:31:17.210
suggest.
And so, the pulse period obeys

00:31:17.210 --> 00:31:22.910
the same rules in terms of its
length as wavelengths of light

00:31:22.910 --> 00:31:27.920
do.
Okay.

00:31:27.920 --> 00:31:33.615
So, for example,
it is true that Δ pulse period

00:31:33.615 --> 00:31:41.370
over pulse period is equal to
the usual Doppler shift formula,

00:31:47.240 --> 00:31:53.356
which is approximately equal to
V_R / c,

00:31:53.356 --> 00:31:57.365
in the Newtonian approximation.
Oh, and I should say,

00:31:57.365 --> 00:31:59.628
in problem one on the problem
set, you can use the Newtonian

00:31:59.628 --> 00:32:02.037
approximation,
because, as you'll discover,

00:32:02.037 --> 00:32:05.742
the velocity of the object as
it goes around in its orbit is

00:32:05.742 --> 00:32:08.630
significantly less than the
speed of light.

00:32:08.630 --> 00:32:15.154
Okay.
So, they discover this Binary

00:32:15.154 --> 00:32:21.019
Pulsar with a short orbital
period.

00:32:21.019 --> 00:32:24.984
The orbital period--this is now
the orbital period--is around

00:32:24.984 --> 00:32:28.816
eight hours, which is pretty
short, but it's still not very

00:32:28.816 --> 00:32:31.783
relativistic.
But you can measure these

00:32:31.783 --> 00:32:34.070
things to incredible accuracy.

00:32:41.170 --> 00:32:45.582
So, you cannot only see the
velocity curve that we're used

00:32:45.582 --> 00:32:47.947
to.
You can also see tiny

00:32:47.947 --> 00:32:52.279
deviations from the Newtonian
velocity curve.

00:32:52.279 --> 00:32:55.843
And from those tiny deviations
from the Newtonian velocity

00:32:55.843 --> 00:32:58.970
curve, you can see these
post-Newtonian effects.

00:32:58.970 --> 00:33:04.108
In particular,
it turns out--so this in an

00:33:04.108 --> 00:33:08.030
elliptical orbit.
It's not a circular orbit.

00:33:08.030 --> 00:33:12.710
It's a highly elliptical orbit.
And you can see the precession

00:33:12.710 --> 00:33:18.366
of the periastron as the
ellipticity--as the direction of

00:33:18.366 --> 00:33:21.223
the orbit,
as the position of the orbit,

00:33:21.223 --> 00:33:24.150
changes, you can see the
precession of the periastron.

00:33:24.150 --> 00:33:28.127
And the precession of the
periastron happens at the rate

00:33:28.127 --> 00:33:32.942
of four degrees per year.
Now, compare that to Mercury,

00:33:32.942 --> 00:33:38.964
in which the same effect can be
observed at 43 arc seconds per

00:33:38.964 --> 00:33:42.557
century.
So, this is a much stronger

00:33:42.557 --> 00:33:43.300
effect.

00:33:48.410 --> 00:33:53.059
Okay.
You can also see the

00:33:53.059 --> 00:33:55.700
gravitational redshift.

00:34:03.609 --> 00:34:05.540
Now, let me show you how this
comes about.

00:34:08.559 --> 00:34:10.846
But you have to be careful
about exactly what you're

00:34:10.846 --> 00:34:12.674
seeing.
You're not seeing the

00:34:12.674 --> 00:34:16.269
gravitational redshift,
due to the fact that the clock

00:34:16.269 --> 00:34:20.320
is sitting on a neutron star.
Because, okay,

00:34:20.320 --> 00:34:28.515
you're seeing the effect of the
companion object of this other

00:34:28.515 --> 00:34:33.470
object in the system,
which happens to be also a

00:34:33.470 --> 00:34:35.600
neutron star,
but not a pulsar.

00:34:38.990 --> 00:34:42.906
And what happens is this.
Here's your clock,

00:34:42.906 --> 00:34:47.220
and it's going around in some
kind of elliptical orbit.

00:34:47.220 --> 00:34:49.739
Here's the center of mass.
Here's the other;

00:34:49.739 --> 00:34:54.019
so, there's a clock that's
going around like this.

00:34:54.019 --> 00:34:59.446
And then, there's some other
object that's going around like

00:34:59.446 --> 00:35:01.173
this.
They're approximately the same

00:35:01.173 --> 00:35:01.390
mass.

00:35:04.400 --> 00:35:07.670
And so, sometimes these objects
are close to each other.

00:35:07.670 --> 00:35:12.745
For example,
here--when they're here and

00:35:12.745 --> 00:35:17.690
here, this is--call this
position 1.

00:35:17.690 --> 00:35:20.760
And then, later on,
half an orbit later,

00:35:20.760 --> 00:35:25.640
they're out here in position 2,
and this one's gone all the way

00:35:25.640 --> 00:35:29.889
out to here.
So, at position 1,

00:35:29.889 --> 00:35:38.692
the objects are close,
and so, the clock is redshifted

00:35:38.692 --> 00:35:45.170
by the presence of the other
object.

00:35:45.170 --> 00:35:49.396
And so, it has to--there's a
redshift due to the other

00:35:49.396 --> 00:35:55.054
object, which is nearby.
Objects are close,

00:35:55.054 --> 00:36:05.809
so, the redshift caused by the
other object is large.

00:36:05.809 --> 00:36:13.078
At position 2 the distance to
the other object is much

00:36:13.078 --> 00:36:19.980
greater--distance is greater.
And so, redshift is less.

00:36:24.150 --> 00:36:27.446
Now, it's also true that
there's a redshift caused by the

00:36:27.446 --> 00:36:30.389
fact that this clock is sitting
on neutron star.

00:36:30.389 --> 00:36:32.719
But the thing about that
redshift is it doesn't change

00:36:32.719 --> 00:36:35.986
during the course of the orbit.
So, you can't actually tell

00:36:35.986 --> 00:36:38.737
that it's there.
Because that's one of the

00:36:38.737 --> 00:36:42.403
differences between measuring
pulse periods of pulsars and

00:36:42.403 --> 00:36:46.359
measuring wavelengths of light.
With these spectral features in

00:36:46.359 --> 00:36:49.270
light, you know what it's
supposed to be if it isn't

00:36:49.270 --> 00:36:51.583
redshifted.
In the case of the pulsars you

00:36:51.583 --> 00:36:54.257
don't know, in advance,
what the pulse period ought to

00:36:54.257 --> 00:36:56.254
be.
So, you can't tell what it

00:36:56.254 --> 00:36:59.772
should be if there was no
gravitational field or was no

00:36:59.772 --> 00:37:02.557
Doppler shift.
All that you can tell is the

00:37:02.557 --> 00:37:05.971
amount by which it changes
during the course of an orbital

00:37:05.971 --> 00:37:08.475
period.
And so, you're comparing the

00:37:08.475 --> 00:37:12.831
redshift when the objects are in
this position to the redshift of

00:37:12.831 --> 00:37:16.839
the objects in this position.
The redshift caused by the

00:37:16.839 --> 00:37:20.710
pulsar itself doesn't change,
but the redshift caused by

00:37:20.710 --> 00:37:23.992
where its companion is,
and the gravitational force

00:37:23.992 --> 00:37:26.090
exerted by the companion,
does change.

00:37:26.090 --> 00:37:28.507
The consequence,
by the way, is that if these

00:37:28.507 --> 00:37:31.726
things are in a circular orbit,
you can't see the gravitational

00:37:31.726 --> 00:37:34.631
redshift, because they're always
the same distance away from each

00:37:34.631 --> 00:37:36.618
other,
and the gravitational redshift

00:37:36.618 --> 00:37:38.784
doesn't change.
There is a gravitational

00:37:38.784 --> 00:37:42.261
redshift, but it doesn't change
during the course of the period,

00:37:42.261 --> 00:37:44.690
and it's the change that you
can observe.

00:37:44.690 --> 00:37:46.500
Yes?
Student: So,

00:37:46.500 --> 00:37:48.717
in this case,
redshift refers not to the

00:37:48.717 --> 00:37:51.389
frequency of,
like, the light in the pulses?

00:37:51.389 --> 00:37:53.373
It refers to the [Inaudible]
Professor Charles

00:37:53.373 --> 00:37:55.150
Bailyn: It's the time
between pulses.

00:37:55.150 --> 00:37:57.991
Yeah.
You could imagine that the

00:37:57.991 --> 00:38:01.027
pulses might have a spectral
feature and then you would see

00:38:01.027 --> 00:38:02.860
it in the spectral feature,
too.

00:38:02.860 --> 00:38:05.060
In fact, that's extremely hard
to have that.

00:38:05.060 --> 00:38:09.159
That doesn't happen.
It's a continuum of light.

00:38:09.159 --> 00:38:12.938
So it's the time--what you
observe is the time between

00:38:12.938 --> 00:38:14.915
pulses.
And that can be observed

00:38:14.915 --> 00:38:17.709
extremely accurately.
You get 20 decimal places of

00:38:17.709 --> 00:38:21.070
accuracy.
It's really kind of frightening.

00:38:21.070 --> 00:38:24.861
Yes?
Student: [Inaudible]

00:38:24.861 --> 00:38:28.153
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Well,

00:38:28.153 --> 00:38:31.000
if it's a circular orbit,
no.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.014
If there's a circular orbit,
they're always the same

00:38:33.014 --> 00:38:35.273
distance around each other.
They're chasing each other

00:38:35.273 --> 00:38:37.484
around in a circle.
That's what it means to be

00:38:37.484 --> 00:38:39.830
circular orbit,
if every point on the orbit is

00:38:39.830 --> 00:38:42.539
the same distance to the center
for both objects.

00:38:42.539 --> 00:38:46.566
So, each object is the same
distance from the center of mass

00:38:46.566 --> 00:38:48.976
at all times.
That's what makes it a circular

00:38:48.976 --> 00:38:50.466
orbit.
And they're always on the

00:38:50.466 --> 00:38:53.290
opposite side of the center of
mass, so, the distance between

00:38:53.290 --> 00:38:55.550
them is always the same for a
circular orbit.

00:38:55.550 --> 00:38:58.289
I'll draw it.
Here we go.

00:38:58.289 --> 00:39:02.060
Here's the center of mass,
supposing these objects are the

00:39:02.060 --> 00:39:04.735
same mass as each other.
Here's one of them,

00:39:04.735 --> 00:39:07.400
it's going around this way and
here it is right now.

00:39:07.400 --> 00:39:11.578
And here's the other object,
it's going around this way,

00:39:11.578 --> 00:39:15.245
and here it is right now.
And they're just going to march

00:39:15.245 --> 00:39:17.852
around this circle,
each being on the opposite side

00:39:17.852 --> 00:39:20.980
of the center and the distance
between them won't change.

00:39:20.980 --> 00:39:24.211
Student: [Inaudible]
Professor Charles

00:39:24.211 --> 00:39:27.167
Bailyn: Oh,
they only overlap if the two

00:39:27.167 --> 00:39:31.530
objects are the same mass.
So, if one object is more

00:39:31.530 --> 00:39:36.499
massive than the other,
then you've got a little circle

00:39:36.499 --> 00:39:41.099
going this way and a big circle
going this way.

00:39:41.099 --> 00:39:43.219
Let's see, it would have to be
there.

00:39:43.219 --> 00:39:46.061
And then, they're still the
same distance from each other at

00:39:46.061 --> 00:39:48.971
every point along the way.
Because each one of them is

00:39:48.971 --> 00:39:51.748
always the same distance from
the center of mass,

00:39:51.748 --> 00:39:54.293
in the middle,
and they're always on opposite

00:39:54.293 --> 00:39:57.180
sides.
Student: [Inaudible]

00:39:57.180 --> 00:40:00.098
Professor Charles
Bailyn: So,

00:40:00.098 --> 00:40:04.349
the way ellipses work is--so,
here's an ellipse.

00:40:04.349 --> 00:40:08.000
And the ellipse can be big or
little--here's an ellipse.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:11.857
They're doing ellipses,
and the center of mass is at

00:40:11.857 --> 00:40:15.388
one focus of the ellipse.
It's not at the center of the

00:40:15.388 --> 00:40:17.309
ellipse.
That's the key thing.

00:40:17.309 --> 00:40:20.058
And so, when you're furthest
away from the focus,

00:40:20.058 --> 00:40:22.519
you have a long distance from
the center.

00:40:22.519 --> 00:40:24.800
When you're closer,
you're closer.

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:26.495
And it's because,
each one of these things,

00:40:26.495 --> 00:40:28.756
you don't maintain a constant
distance from the center of

00:40:28.756 --> 00:40:29.120
mass.

00:40:33.960 --> 00:40:38.241
Okay, so, because of this
effect in elliptical orbits,

00:40:38.241 --> 00:40:41.392
in Binary Pulsars,
in elliptical orbits,

00:40:41.392 --> 00:40:45.190
you can observe the
gravitational redshift.

00:40:45.190 --> 00:40:49.185
Also – and this is what they
got the Nobel Prize for,

00:40:49.185 --> 00:40:53.550
really – you can see that the
orbital period decreases.

00:40:53.550 --> 00:40:56.037
It's getting shorter.
The two objects are spiraling

00:40:56.037 --> 00:40:56.660
in together.

00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:04.710
Decreases due to gravitational
waves.

00:41:07.909 --> 00:41:12.822
So, you can observe three
different post-Newtonian effects

00:41:12.822 --> 00:41:18.056
in these systems.
So, this constitutes a serious

00:41:18.056 --> 00:41:23.929
test of general relativity in
the following way.

00:41:23.929 --> 00:41:30.648
If you could do only Newtonian
measurements,

00:41:30.648 --> 00:41:35.352
what would you get?
Well, we did this before,

00:41:35.352 --> 00:41:37.412
for the planets.
What you can get out of a

00:41:37.412 --> 00:41:39.291
Newtonian measurement of
velocity--remember,

00:41:39.291 --> 00:41:41.869
what you're doing is you're
measuring the Doppler shift;

00:41:41.869 --> 00:41:43.440
you're measuring radial
velocity.

00:41:43.440 --> 00:41:46.873
What you get is,
you can determine

00:41:46.873 --> 00:41:52.490
M_total,
the total mass of the system,

00:41:52.490 --> 00:41:57.016
if you know the inclination.
That's something we tended to

00:41:57.016 --> 00:41:58.535
leave out.
We always claim these things

00:41:58.535 --> 00:42:00.590
are edge-on because it makes the
calculations easier.

00:42:00.590 --> 00:42:02.530
But, in fact,
you get a different answer

00:42:02.530 --> 00:42:04.322
depending on what the
inclination is,

00:42:04.322 --> 00:42:06.860
and you don't necessarily know
the inclination.

00:42:06.860 --> 00:42:13.146
So, if you now measure the
precession of the periastron,

00:42:13.146 --> 00:42:18.748
then this also--the amount of
that also depends on

00:42:18.748 --> 00:42:23.549
M_1,
M_2,

00:42:23.549 --> 00:42:28.349
the two masses,
and the inclination.

00:42:28.349 --> 00:42:31.789
So, you can solve for the
inclination now.

00:42:31.789 --> 00:42:34.764
This isn't actually precisely
how you do it,

00:42:34.764 --> 00:42:37.599
but conceptually,
this is how it works.

00:42:37.599 --> 00:42:39.889
You now solve for the
inclination.

00:42:39.889 --> 00:42:44.824
You then know
M_total,

00:42:44.824 --> 00:42:50.665
but not each individual mass.
Student: [Inaudible]

00:42:50.665 --> 00:42:52.750
Professor Charles
Bailyn:

00:42:52.750 --> 00:42:56.046
M_1,
M_2 and the

00:42:56.046 --> 00:42:58.400
inclination, this is i.

00:43:02.030 --> 00:43:03.829
But you don't know the
individual masses.

00:43:03.829 --> 00:43:08.009
Now, if both objects were
pulsars and you could see both

00:43:08.009 --> 00:43:12.340
orbits, then you would also know
the individual masses.

00:43:12.340 --> 00:43:14.992
But you don't.
You only see one of these

00:43:14.992 --> 00:43:16.570
objects.
Okay.

00:43:16.570 --> 00:43:21.550
So, now, the next effect is
gravitational redshift.

00:43:26.090 --> 00:43:29.676
And this, again,
depends, in a different way,

00:43:29.676 --> 00:43:33.343
on M_1,
M_2,

00:43:33.343 --> 00:43:39.320
and the inclination.
And so, now you can solve for

00:43:39.320 --> 00:43:44.431
M_1.
And since you know the total

00:43:44.431 --> 00:43:47.449
mass, you also get
M_2.

00:43:47.449 --> 00:43:50.693
So, at this point you know
M_1,

00:43:50.693 --> 00:43:53.659
M_2 and the
inclination.

00:43:53.659 --> 00:43:56.633
What's happening here is that
each time you measure an effect,

00:43:56.633 --> 00:43:58.340
you get an additional
constraint.

00:43:58.340 --> 00:44:03.639
And you started out having
three unknowns and one equation.

00:44:03.639 --> 00:44:05.850
And, of course,
you can't solve for three

00:44:05.850 --> 00:44:10.391
unknowns with only one equation.
But then, you observe two more

00:44:10.391 --> 00:44:12.426
effects.
So, now, you have three

00:44:12.426 --> 00:44:15.993
unknowns and three equations.
So, now, you can solve for all

00:44:15.993 --> 00:44:19.289
of these things.
Now you know everything.

00:44:19.289 --> 00:44:24.818
At this point you can predict
what the period change should

00:44:24.818 --> 00:44:28.060
be, because you know everything.

00:44:32.440 --> 00:44:35.889
Then you can measure that.
And so, you have a specific

00:44:35.889 --> 00:44:39.230
prediction created from general
relativity.

00:44:39.230 --> 00:44:43.922
You can measure this effect,
and the prediction turns out to

00:44:43.922 --> 00:44:47.660
be correct, to within the
measurement errors.

00:44:51.980 --> 00:44:55.232
And the measurement errors are
getting more precise all the

00:44:55.232 --> 00:44:58.373
time, because as time goes on
the amount of change in the

00:44:58.373 --> 00:45:00.440
period,
since they first observe it,

00:45:00.440 --> 00:45:02.606
increases.
Because the period's changing

00:45:02.606 --> 00:45:05.798
more, it's slowing down and the
period's getting faster and

00:45:05.798 --> 00:45:07.889
faster, the objects are falling
in.

00:45:07.889 --> 00:45:12.019
And so, over time that change
mounts up.

00:45:12.019 --> 00:45:14.333
You can measure it better and
better and better as time goes

00:45:14.333 --> 00:45:16.637
on.
And so, the precision of this

00:45:16.637 --> 00:45:20.489
test of general relativity is
going up all the time.

00:45:20.489 --> 00:45:28.638
So, it is now clear that
general relativity is correct,

00:45:28.638 --> 00:45:33.920
to some number of decimal
places.

00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:36.802
I'm going to put correct in
quotes, because it depends how

00:45:36.802 --> 00:45:40.695
accurately you can measure it,
but the accuracy is going up

00:45:40.695 --> 00:45:44.840
all the time--in the
post-Newtonian approximation.

00:45:44.840 --> 00:45:50.210
Remember, all these effects are
post-Newtonian only.

00:45:50.210 --> 00:45:54.154
Actually, they've now observed
a couple of post-post-Newtonian

00:45:54.154 --> 00:45:57.969
effects, which are the next term
in the series expansion.

00:45:57.969 --> 00:46:01.078
And those are also correct,
but they're not measured as

00:46:01.078 --> 00:46:04.912
precisely yet.
So, it's clear that general

00:46:04.912 --> 00:46:11.815
relativity is correct as long as
everything is still pretty close

00:46:11.815 --> 00:46:16.016
to the Newtonian thing.
You can actually still have

00:46:16.016 --> 00:46:21.664
orbits.
But you could imagine a theory

00:46:21.664 --> 00:46:31.610
which is like Newton in the
first term of the expansion,

00:46:31.610 --> 00:46:43.604
like general relativity in the
second term, the post-Newtonian

00:46:43.604 --> 00:46:55.010
term, but different in very
strong gravitational fields.

00:46:55.010 --> 00:46:57.210
So, you've got to get the first
term to work,

00:46:57.210 --> 00:46:59.159
and it's got to come out like
Newton.

00:46:59.159 --> 00:47:00.619
You've got to get the second
term to work.

00:47:00.619 --> 00:47:02.940
It's got to come out like
general relativity.

00:47:02.940 --> 00:47:06.828
But then, you can imagine all
sorts of different functions

00:47:06.828 --> 00:47:09.215
that work with this,
work with this,

00:47:09.215 --> 00:47:12.489
and are different in the higher
order terms.

00:47:12.489 --> 00:47:15.804
And the higher order terms are
the things that give rise to all

00:47:15.804 --> 00:47:18.103
these exciting effects,
like event horizons,

00:47:18.103 --> 00:47:24.388
and things like that.
So, what would be nice--it

00:47:24.388 --> 00:47:36.570
would be good to have some way
of testing strong field effects.

00:47:36.570 --> 00:47:40.266
And by that,
I mean, situations in which the

00:47:40.266 --> 00:47:45.079
Schwarzschild radius over
r becomes close to 1.

00:47:45.079 --> 00:47:48.566
Because, in that case,
all the terms in this series

00:47:48.566 --> 00:47:51.962
expansion, contribute.
And, if you can get it--if the

00:47:51.962 --> 00:47:54.890
theory is right there,
then all the terms have to be

00:47:54.890 --> 00:47:57.262
the same,
and you don't have this nagging

00:47:57.262 --> 00:48:00.410
doubt about whether you could
come up with some theory that

00:48:00.410 --> 00:48:03.139
looks like Newton,
in the same way that general

00:48:03.139 --> 00:48:06.431
relativity looks like Newton,
but is different once you get

00:48:06.431 --> 00:48:08.986
higher order terms.
Looks like general relativity

00:48:08.986 --> 00:48:11.148
in the second term,
but turns out to be a totally

00:48:11.148 --> 00:48:13.099
different theory.
Needless to say,

00:48:13.099 --> 00:48:15.852
the theorists have come up
with, literally,

00:48:15.852 --> 00:48:18.409
an infinite number of such
theories.

00:48:18.409 --> 00:48:21.543
Because there's a whole
infinite family of things which

00:48:21.543 --> 00:48:23.052
satisfy this,
satisfy this,

00:48:23.052 --> 00:48:25.489
and look different at the upper
level.

00:48:25.489 --> 00:48:30.324
So, what we're going to talk
about next time is how one might

00:48:30.324 --> 00:48:33.789
go about testing strong field
relativity.

00:48:33.789 --> 00:48:37.265
This is a subject close to my
heart because it's what I do for

00:48:37.265 --> 00:48:40.000
a living, and we'll talk about
it on Thursday.

